<div class="prose">

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">📌 Why these words?</div>
  <p>This unit asks: what makes a planet habitable? You will compare Earth, Mars, and a chosen exoplanet against a framework of habitability criteria. The vocabulary below gives you the precise scientific language for that comparison.</p>
</div>

<h2>Vocabulary</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Term</th>
      <th>What it means + visual cue</th>
      <th>Sentence stem</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Habitability</strong></td>
      <td>The capacity of a planet or environment to support life as we know it. <em>Visual: Planet with a small house icon on it.</em></td>
      <td>A planet is habitable if it has ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Habitable zone (HZ)</strong></td>
      <td>The range of distances from a star where a planet's surface temperature could allow liquid water. <em>Visual: Ring around a sun showing the "just right" distance band.</em></td>
      <td>This planet sits inside / outside the habitable zone because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Astronomical unit (AU)</strong></td>
      <td>The average distance from Earth to the Sun, about 150 million kilometers. Used as a ruler for our solar system. <em>Visual: Ruler stretching from Sun to Earth labeled "1 AU."</em></td>
      <td>This planet orbits at ___ AU from its star.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Light-year</strong></td>
      <td>The distance light travels in one year, about 9.5 trillion kilometers. Used to measure distances between stars. <em>Visual: Beam of light with a 1-year clock.</em></td>
      <td>This star is ___ light-years from Earth, which means we see it as it was ___ years ago.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Exoplanet</strong></td>
      <td>A planet that orbits a star other than our Sun. <em>Visual: Planet circling a star other than the Sun.</em></td>
      <td>The exoplanet I am studying is ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Transit</strong></td>
      <td>When a planet passes in front of its star from our viewpoint, causing the star's light to dim slightly. The main way we detect exoplanets. <em>Visual: Star's light curve dipping briefly when a planet crosses in front.</em></td>
      <td>We detected this exoplanet by observing a transit, which means ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Atmosphere</strong></td>
      <td>The layer of gases surrounding a planet, held by gravity. Determines temperature, weather, and protection from radiation. <em>Visual: Blue halo around Earth.</em></td>
      <td>This planet's atmosphere is mostly ___, which affects ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Magnetic field</strong></td>
      <td>An invisible region around a planet that deflects charged particles from its star. Protects the atmosphere and any surface life. <em>Visual: Curved lines wrapping around a planet like a shield.</em></td>
      <td>This planet has / lacks a strong magnetic field, which means ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Subsystem</strong></td>
      <td>A smaller system that is part of a larger system. Earth's subsystems include the atmosphere, hydrosphere, geosphere, and biosphere. <em>Visual: Russian-doll nested circles labeled Earth → atmosphere.</em></td>
      <td>The ___ subsystem affects the ___ subsystem by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Feedback loop</strong></td>
      <td>When the output of a system loops back to change its input. Positive feedback amplifies change; negative feedback dampens it. <em>Visual: Circular arrow showing output flowing back to input.</em></td>
      <td>This is a positive / negative feedback loop because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Greenhouse effect</strong></td>
      <td>Atmospheric gases trap heat from the planet's surface, raising temperature. Necessary for habitability on Earth; runaway on Venus. <em>Visual: Sun's rays entering atmosphere, some heat trapped inside.</em></td>
      <td>Without the greenhouse effect, Earth would be ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Systems thinking</strong></td>
      <td>Looking at how parts interact within a whole, instead of analyzing parts in isolation. <em>Visual: Web of arrows connecting multiple boxes.</em></td>
      <td>Using systems thinking, I can see that ___ connects to ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Scale</strong></td>
      <td>The size or extent of something. In this unit: spatial scale (kilometers to light-years) and time scale (seconds to billions of years). <em>Visual: Number line with logarithmic tick marks from atoms to galaxies.</em></td>
      <td>This process happens at the scale of ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Equilibrium</strong></td>
      <td>A balanced state where competing processes cancel out. Earth's climate equilibrium can shift if inputs change. <em>Visual: Balance scale at rest with equal weights on each side.</em></td>
      <td>This system is in / out of equilibrium because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Habitability framework</strong></td>
      <td>The set of criteria you will apply to each planet: distance from star, atmosphere, water, magnetic protection, surface conditions, etc. <em>Visual: Checklist with criteria boxes.</em></td>
      <td>On the habitability framework, this planet scores ___ on ___.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">🛠️ In-class pre-teach activity (8 min)</div>
  <p><strong>Picture-match.</strong> I will show you 6 images: Earth, Mars, Venus, a hot Jupiter, an ocean world, and a frozen rocky planet. For each, write down 2 vocabulary terms from this list that apply. We will discuss as a class.</p>
</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">💬 Paired discussion prompt</div>
  <p>With a partner: pick one habitability criterion. Argue (in 2-3 sentences each) which is more important for life — being in the habitable zone, or having a magnetic field. Use at least two terms from this list.</p>
</div>

